Background - Original Project

The goal is to produce a three-part series on the impact of inflation on financial decision-making of NYC households with low incomesâspecifically for communities of color and women. The motivating questions for the briefs are as follows:

Issue Brief #1: Which expenses rise the most in NYC compared to other cities and states?

See a detailed scope for Issue Brief #1 here.

Issue Brief #2: How do NYC residents approach rising prices, what budget decisions and tradeoffs are made, and what coping strategies are used?

Potential data source: New York City data derived from OFE clients.

Issue Brief #3: What are policy recommendations for future efforts that effectively address the unique rising costs of household with low-income?

OFE has a unique contribution to the national conversation. First, OFE can lend an equity-focused lens from its programs work and access to partners and participants for qualitative research. Second, as the supports for addressing rising prices continues into the future, it can profile considerations and make specific recommendations.

See a more detailed project plan here.

An overview of the publicly available data at our disposable is here.

The first spreadsheet, data-summary, presents a summary of the available data that can characterize inflation in NYC and in relation to the US and other metropolitan areas.

We can ask and answer the following general questions:

  1. How have prices changed over time in the NYC metro area?

The Bureau of Labor Statistics data offer insights into this.

  1. How have prices changed over time in the NYC metro area compared to another metro area?

The Bureau of Labor Statistics data offer insights into this.

  1. How has household spending among NY residents been affected during the pandemic?

The Census data offer insights into this.

The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics has the necessary Consumer Price Index data to analyze inflation, using index values, for all items for the NYC metropolitan area and other urban areas from 2012 to present.

Challenges

Some of the major challenges that have been communicated or we have encountered:

  • Data: The publicly available data arenât specific to NYC.
    • The BLS data on inflation rates covers the NYC metropolitan area, which includes parts of NJ and PA.
    • The Census data on household spending behavior covers the NYC metropolitan area, which includes parts of NJ and PA.. The data are experimental but perhaps sufficient to tackle the question. Another option is to collect data from our own clients, and frame our findings appropriatelyâparticularly for Issue #2.


  • Relevancy: Due to the external review process, the timeliness of each brief, by the date of publication, will be affected.

  • Politics: The Mayor may not want to publish anything that brings more attention to inflation.


Options

  • #1. Issue Briefs
    (Publication)
  • #2. Summary/Infographic
    (Publication)
  • #3. Dashboard
    (Web App)

Proceed with the Issue Briefs. Revisit other ideas if there is a challenge with publishing one of these briefs.

We have the data to tackle Issue Briefs #1 and #2 to varying extents.

But what are the implications for Issue Brief #3?

Create an economic summary, like the BLS, that repackages the same BLS-derived data for the NYC metropolitan area, but in a cleaner, more compact data visualization format.

This could be a more timely product. Although informational, it could be distributed to program providers and/or clients.

But how could this serve or relate to low-income New Yorkers, especially among specific subgroups (e.g., race and gender)?

Develop a web application that presents updates about inflation in the NYC metropolitan area. This is similar to the previous summary/infographic alternative, but is a strictly web-based product that also offers the ability for consumers to use the app for their needsâe.g., calculating estimated inflation for a certain item between two time points.

This could be a more timely product. Although informational, it could be used by clients or visitors to the DCWP website.

But how could this serve or relate to low-income New Yorkers, especially among specific subgroups (e.g., race and gender)?
